flowRoot.flowPara: Time spent and left of transient states in stationary populations

In stationary multistate populations, the distribution of individuals in a given state by time spent continuously in that state is identical to (or symmetrical to) the distribution by time left in that state. We aim to prove this symmetry.

This might be useful to know because if you can estimate one of these distributions then you can infer the other. Specifically, it might be helpful to devise a way to estimate the unobserved age pattern of onset for health conditions.
Any R code or LaTeX related to this work is available in a public repository, including while in development:
https://github.com/timriffe/TransientSymmetry

Stationary populations are more symmetrical with respect to time spent and left than has been previously described. We give an intuitive proof that the distributions of time spent and left are equal within states in stationary populations. We hope that this relationship may inspire new measurement approaches. We think that that researchers working with censored or truncated data or any kind of multistate models should be generally aware of this equality in case it may come in handy as a heuristic.

The transient tenure symmetry we describe here is also tractable in stable populations, but we have not investigated this extension in detail. Future research, potentially more sophisticated simulations, should aim to establish the impact of departures from stationarity and suggest bounds of usability for this relationship.
Francisco Villavicencio and Tim Riffe (2016) Symmetries between life lived and left in finite stationary populations, Demographic Research. V. 34, pp 381-398
Tim Riffe and Nicolas Brouard (2018) Structure and dynamics of populations: The ‘years-to-live’ pyramid, national aspects and regional examples. Socarxiv. An English translation of:
Brouard, Nicolas (1986) Structure et dynamique des populations. La pyramide des années à vivre, aspects nationaux et exemples régionaux. Espace, Populations, Sociétés vol.4 n°2, pp. 157-168

Symmetry between years lived and years left is a known property of single state stationary populations, the Brouard-Carey Equality. This equality has been helpful in biodemography and historical demography, where age is sometimes unobserved, but followup to death is possible.

That multistate stationary populations produce the expectation of a fixed multistate trajectory composition is known. We illustrate this point with an example, for clarity, because it is a property we use to prove a Brouard-Carey symmetry for states in multistate stationary populations.

As an example, let's generate a multistate stationary population. It doesn't matter how: We'll do a Markov generation process, but it could be something else. Define a 2-state model (healthy-sick) with 6 discrete age classes.

flowRoot.flowPara: If each mortality schedule is closed out with 1, then the sum of the probabilities of all possible trajectories is 1. Under stationarity this composition is fixed. That means everything about it is fixed.
Matrix-based models calculate the fundamental matrix, which has a fixed age-state occupancy composition like this.
The trajectory composition can be collapsed in other ways, though, to learn something about episode structure.

Each trajectory has a single probability of occurring, allowing us to weight each possible trajectory to determine the stationary population composition (middle).

text.tspan: Imagine a person living through the
episode. Over the episode, we click
a special stopwatch in regular intervals.
The stopwatch is also a countdown
timer, so every time you click, it saves
both elapsed time since start and time
left until the end. With appropriate
rounding, the two sets of values will
be identical, and that's true by appeal
to intuition (no need to prove it).

flowRoot.flowPara: Once in stationary renewal, the probability of observing this very episode in exactly the same way is fixed in each time interval. If renewal is happening in lock-step with age (as in discrete Lexis steps), then we expect to see each time spent and time left value of this episode simultaneously, but over sequentially replicated life trajectories.

flowRoot.flowPara: The same must hold in the period cross section for episodes from distinct trajectories that are subject to stationary renewal. That is, by induction, we can keep concatenating time spent and left values as of a hypothetical census on the whole population and the supersets A and T are expected to be equal. This owes to the stationary trajectory composition, itself derived from fixed transition rates.

text.tspan: Aside: related things that are not symmetrical

flowRoot.flowPara: The stationary trajectory composition is not symmetrical in the aggregate Brouard-Carey sense.
The resulting multistate occupancy patterns are
not symmetrical.
The resulting multistate prevalence patterns are
also not symmetrical.
